Settle showed up in Week 7, notching four solos, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Settle is up to three sacks on the season but has been too inconsistent in the solo department to trust as anything more than a DT2/3. Keep him benched for Week 8 despite his reappearance in the sack column.

DeMarcus Walker had his strongest outing of the season in Week 6, tallying four solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The sack was his first of the season. Walker should continue to be treated as a depth piece only. He is not even a flex2 option for Week 8 due to no teams being on bye. Look elsewhere.

Golston saw his snap count drop drastically compared to Week 5 but still managed to record three solos, two assists, 0.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. He still played 66 percent of the snaps but could continue to lose snaps to K.J. Henry and Carl Lawson, especially coming off a bye. Keep Golston benched for Week 8 against the San Francisco 49ers.

Paschal showed up in Week 7, tallying four solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. It was his first sack of the season, so we will need to see more before deploying him or even rostering him outside of the deepest of leagues. Look elsewhere for Week 8.

Roqaun was excellent in Week 7, racking up 11 solos, seven assists, and one forced fumble. Roquan remains locked in as a top-10 option and should be an elite play for Week 8, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Zaire was at it again in Week 7, reeling off five solos, 11 assists, and one forced fumble. Zaire has recorded five or more solos in five of his last six games and should continue to be counted as a top-10 option.

Pratt was at it again in Week 7, tallying 10 solos and three assists. Pratt has recorded five or more solos in each of his last six games and has recorded six or more in five of those six. Treat Pratt as a top-15 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Ivan Pace was excellent in Week 7, notching three solos, seven assists, one sack, one fumble recovery, and one touchdown. Pace has been an IDP force when he has been on the field this season and should continue to be counted as a top-25 option for Week 8 and beyond. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Dorian continued his strong play in Week 7, racking up six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Williams has recorded five or more solos in six of his seven games and is locked in as a top-20 option regardless of opponent. Treat him as such for Week 8, despite a neutral at best matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Lloyd was excellent in Week 7, tallying five solos, six assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. It was his best fantasy output of the season, so hopefully, this is a sign of more LB1 production to come. Tap Llyod as a top-25 option for Week 8, thanks to a plus matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Barton exploded on Thursday Night Football, going off for six solos, two assists, one sack, one pass defended, one forced fumble, one fumble recovery, and one touchdown. Barton has been inconsistent but has now recorded six or more solos in two of his last three games. This monster performance ensures that he will remain locked in as a starter for the remainder of the season and highlights some of the upside the Broncos thought they were getting when they added him this offseason. Barton is an LB3 with LB2 upside for Week 8 but will be an LB2 option when the byes resume.

Dean was elite in Week 7, racking up six solos, five assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Dean now has five or more solos in three straight games and has bullied his way into the top-20 conversation. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals. Dean should be rostered in all competitive leagues.

Anzalone was excellent in Week 7, tallying seven solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. Anzalone has five or more solos in all three of his complete games and should be counted as an LB2 option for Week 8, thanks to a plus matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Strnad was at it again in Week 7, racking up six solos, three assists, and one sack. Strnad has been an impact IDP producer since Alex Singleton went down and has recorded five or more solos in three straight games while adding a sack in three of his last four. Strnad should be rostered in all competitive leagues and can be counted as an LB2 option for a tasty Week 8 matchup against the Carolina Panthers. Add him everywhere.

Bernard was excellent in Week 7, recording six solos, two assists, two tackles for loss, and one fumble recovery. Bernard has been inconsistent and has not been the LB1 many had expected but is still a top-tier LB2 play. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Campbell was excellent in Week 7, notching five solos, two assists, and one sack. Campbell has been inconsistent at best this season and is now more LB4 than LB3. Leave Campbell on benches for Week 8 despite the plus matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Stuard went bonkers in Week 7, racking up 11 solos, eight assists, and one tackle for loss. He was awesome in relief of the injured E.J. Speed (knee) and will undoubtedly get another start if Speed misses any more time. He is an automatic LB2 play if he gets another start, but FAAB bids should be tempered accordingly, as there is an all-or-nothing proposition as to whether he has any value for Week 8 or beyond. When Speed returns, he will play an everydown role alongside Zaire Franklin, regardless of how well Stuard does in the interim. Add Stuard wherever needed.

Hewitt impressed again in Week 7, tallying six solos, three assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Hewitt has been producing at an LB2 level with Azeez Al-Shaair sidelined and is worth a look as an LB3 option if Azeez misses more time as expected. Add and start Hewitt as an LB3 with LB2 upside in deeper formats.

Ventrell has played his way into weekly must start territory and should be counted as a top-25 option as long as he is starting. He was solid again in Week 7, tallying six solos and four assists. He has recorded six or more solos in four straight games, emerging as the most consistent LB option on the Jaguars in the absence of Foyesade Oluokun. The LB12 since he started getting regular snaps for the Jaguars, Miller should be started everywhere for Week 8 if Oluokun remains sidelined as expected.

Eric Wilson stepped up after Quay Walker left the game with a concussion, exploding for six solos, two sacks, four tackles for loss, and one pass defended against the Houston Texans. It was an impressive day for the Packers' defense on a whole, but Wilson was a standout. Wilson only has value if Quay ends up missing this weekend's contest against Jacksonville, but after this performance becomes a must-start if Quay misses time as expected. Tap Wilson as an upside LB3 option if Quay is ruled out.

Rodrigo showed up in Week 7, tallying five solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 53 percent of the snaps. This was just the second time all season that he played more than 50 percent of the snaps and was just his third start. Rodriguez has recorded five or more solos just once this season and has registered four or more just twice. Rodriguez should be on waiver wires in all but the deepest of leagues as long as Alex Anzalone and Jack Campbell are healthy.

Damone was excellent in Week 6, racking up four solos, five assists, 0.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He shined filling in for Eric Kendricks (calf), but with a week off to get healthy, expectations are Kendricks will be healthy for Week 8. If Kendricks cannot go, Damone becomes an instant LB3 with LB2 upside for a plus Week 8 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

AVG exploded in Week 7, tallying six solos, one assist, two sacks, three tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Van Ginkel is up to five sacks on the season, with at least one sack in four of his six games. Treat AVG as a DL2 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against a beat up Los Angeles Rams team.

Branch was solid in Week 7, notching four solos, one interception, and two passes defended. Branch has been a strong DB1 option through seven weeks of the season and should remain a top-12 play as long as he is healthy. This was the first time in six games Branch failed to record at least five solos. Start Branch with confidence for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Love was excellent in Week 7, racking up four solos, five assists, one interception, and one pass defended. The DB5/S2 on the season, Love should continue to be treated as an elite DB1. Treat him as such despite a neural at best Week 8 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Hamilton was excellent in Week 7, racking up seven solos, four assists, and one pass defended. Hamilton has five or more solos in four of his last six contests and should continue to be trusted as a DB1 option.

Winfield was excellent in Week 7, racking up eight solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Winfield has been elite when on the field this season and should continue to be treated as a top-three option at DB.

Dugger was excellent in Week 7, racking up nine solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Dugger has been inconsistent as best this season and is now more low-end DB2 than the DB1 many drafted him to be. Still, he has tremendous weekly upside as his two outings with eight or more solos proves. Tap him as a top-25 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against the New York Jets.

McKinney was back at it in Week 7, reeling off five solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. McKinney's interception streak stopped at five games, but he now has an interception or a sack in six of his seven games played this season. Fire McKinney up as a strong DB2 option as long as he is cooking.

Metellus was excellent in Week 7, tallying four solos, four assists, and one forced fumble. This was just the third time all season Metellus has recorded more than four solos, dropping him from DB2 consideration to more of a DB3. It has been a precipitous fall for the former DB1, but the upside is still there. Start Metellus where needed as a DB3 for a neutral Week 8 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Elliott was solid in Week 7, racking up six solos and one tackle for loss. Elliott has been elite this season and comes into Week 8 as the DB8/S5. Tap him as a DB1 option for Week 8, thanks both to his strong play and a plus matchup against the New York Giants.

Lake was excellent in Week 7, reeling off seven solos and two assists. Lake has five or moe solos in five of his six games this season and has a sack and a tackle for loss in the other. Continue to treat Lake as a top-five option as long as he keeps up his strong play.

Curl went off in Week 7, tallying seven solos, two passes defended, one fumble recovery, and one touchdown. Curl has been overshadowed by tackle magnet Quentin Lake but has still been a solid DB3 option. He has been a disappointment relative to expectations but still provides solid DB3 numbers. Add Curl where needed ahead of a plus Week 8 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Hamlin continues to impress for the Bills, most recently notching three solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Hamlin has now strung together five DB2-level outings in his seven starts, putting him in the top-25 mix going forward. Damar should be rostered in all competitive leagues. Add and start Hamlin as a DB2 option for a tasty Week 8 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Justin Reid showed up in Week 7, tallying six solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. This was just his second game all season with more than four solos, so this is not a stat line to chase. Leave Reid on benches or wires for Week 8.

Donovan Wilson was excellent in Week 6, notching four solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Wilson has been a massive IDP disappointment through six games, so hopefully, this, combined with the bye week, has him rearing to go for Week 8 against the San Francisco 49ers. Still, Wilson is a DB3/4 at best until he proves he can produce anywhere close to the level many had expected coming into the season.

Evan Williams showed up again in Week 7, this time notching six solos and three assists. This was a season-high in solos for Williams and marks the third consecutive game in which he has recorded four or more solos. Evan appears locked in as the free safety as long as the Packers have Javon Bullard in the slot, and should be started as a DB3 in leagues of all sizes. Tap him as a top-36 option for Week 8, thanks to a plus matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Poyer returned from injury to post six solos and two assists in Week 7 and should already be rostered in far more than one percent of Yahoo leagues. Poyer has registered five or more solos in both of his last two complete games and should be trusted as a DB2 option for Week 8. He has a plus matchup against an AFC team and should stay busy enough against the run and the pass to make good on at least DB3 numbers. Tap Poyer as a top-25 option for Week 8 against the Arizona Cardinals.

Mustapha is starting for the injured Talanoa Hufanga and responded with six solos and six assists against the Chiefs. He has more upside than George Odum and could provide DB2 value while Talanoa is sidelined. Deep leaguers should pay special attention here, as Malik is a solid DB3 option as long as he is drawing starts.

Stone was excellent in Week 7, tallying three solos, four assists, one interception, and one pass defended. The pick was Stone's first of the season after placing second in the league with seven interceptions last season, so hopefully, this is a sign of things to come. Stone has been inconsistent on the season as a whole but remains a strong DB3 option week in and week out. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

McCollough showed up again in Week 7, tallying one solo, two interceptions, and two passes defended. McCollough has flashed with an interception in two of his last three games and needs to be rostered in interception heavy formats. He is not going to help you when he is not getting picks, but we cannot ignore a run like this.
